The '''Parker Society''' was a [[text publication society]] set up in 1841 to produce editions of the works of the early Protestant writers of the [[English Reformation]]. It was supported by both the [[High Church]] and [[evangelical]] wings of the [[Church of England]], and was established in reaction against the [[Tractarian]] movement of the 1830s. Its Council was dominated by evangelicals, but not to the exclusion of other views.<ref>{{cite book |author=Peter Toon |title=Evangelical Theology 1833–1856 |year=1979 |publisher=Marshall, Morgan & Scott |isbn=0-551-05582-0 |page=43}}</ref>
In response, a group of Tractarians founded the [[Library of Anglo-Catholic Theology]].<ref>{{cite book |author=Frank M. Turner |title=John Henry Newman: The Challenge to Evangelical Religion |year=2002 |publisher=Yale University Press |isbn=978-0-300-17309-3|pages=357–8}}</ref>
The Society took its name from [[Matthew Parker]] (1504–1575), [[Archbishop of Canterbury]] from 1559 to 1575, and a prominent collector of manuscripts.<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://archive.churchsociety.org/churchman/documents/Cman_122_3_Cinnamond.pdf |title=The Reformed Treasures of the Parker Society |author=Andrew Cinnamond|journal=Churchman|publisher=Church Society |year=2008 |volume=122 |issue=3 |pages=221–242 |access-date=13 Sep 2015}}</ref> It published four or five volumes a year, to 1853.<ref>{{cite book|title=A general index to the publications of the Parker Society|url=https://archive.org/stream/ageneralindextot00unknuoft#page/n827/mode/2up|author=Henry Gough|publisher=The Parker Society|date=1855|access-date=13 Sep 2015|at=Postscript}}</ref>
==Publications== A ''General Index to the Publications of the Parker Society'' was published in 1855 by Henry Gough; the publications are listed on pp. vii–viii.<ref>{{cite book|title=A general index to the publications of the Parker Society|url=https://archive.org/stream/ageneralindextot00unknuoft#page/n13/mode/2up|author=Henry Gough|publisher=The Parker Society|date=1855|access-date=13 Sep 2015|pages=vii–viii}}</ref>
