The museum has an extensive collection of medieval European [[frescoes]], ivory statuettes, [[Reliquary Cross (The Cloisters)|reliquary]] wood and metal shrines and crosses, as well as examples of the very rare [[Gothic boxwood miniature]]s.{{sfn|Ellis| Suda |2016|p= 89}} It has liturgical metalwork vessels and rare pieces of Gothic furniture and metalwork.{{sfn|Rorimer|1948|p=237}} Many pieces are not associated with a particular architectural setting, so their placement in the museum may vary.{{sfn|Young|1979|p=125}} Some of the objects have dramatic provenance, including those plundered from the estates of aristocrats during the [[French Revolutionary Army]]'s occupation of the Southern Netherlands.{{sfn|Ridderbos |Van Veen |Van Buren |2005 |pp= 177 & 194}} The Unicorn tapestries were for a period used by the French army to cover potatoes and keep them from freezing.{{sfn|Tomkins |1970|p= 313}}  The set was purchased by Rockefeller in 1922 and six of the tapestries hung in his New York home until donated to the Metropolitan Museum of Art in 1938.{{sfn|Cavallo|1998|p=15}}

===Illuminated manuscripts===
The museum's collection of [[illuminated book]]s is small, but of exceptional quality. J.P. Morgan was a major early donor, but although his taste leaned heavily towards rare printed and illuminated books,{{sfn|Strouse|2000|p=5}} he donated very few to the Metropolitan, instead preserving them at the Morgan Library.<ref name="Islamic" /> At the same time, the consensus within the Met was that the Cloisters should focus on architectural elements, sculpture and decorative arts to enhance the environmental quality of the institution, whereas manuscripts were considered more suited to the Morgan Library in lower Manhattan.{{sfn|Nickel|Hoffeld|Deuchler|1971|p=1}} The Cloisters' books are today displayed in the Treasury room, and include the French "[[Cloisters Apocalypse]]"  (or "Book of Revelation", c. 1330, probably [[Normandy]]),{{sfn|Deuchler|1969|p=146}} [[Jean Pucelle]]'s "[[Hours of Jeanne d'Evreux]]" (c. 1324–28), the "[[Psalter of Bonne de Luxembourg]]", attributed to [[Jean Le Noir (illuminator)|Jean Le Noir]] and the "[[Belles Heures du Duc de Berry]]" (c. 1399–1416) attributed to the [[Limbourg brothers]].{{sfn |Husband |2008 |p=x}} In 2015 the Cloisters acquired a small Netherlandish [[Book of Hours]] illuminated by [[Simon Bening]].<ref name="SM">"[https://www.metmuseum.org/-/media/Files/About%20The%20Met/Annual%20Reports/2015-2016/Annual%20Report%202015-16%20Report%20from%20the%20Director%20and%20President.pdf Annual Report for the Year 2014–15: Report from the Director and the President]". Metropolitan Museum of Art, November 10, 2015. Retrieved March 30, 2018</ref> Each is of exceptional quality, and their acquisition was a significant achievement for the museum's early collectors.{{sfn|Nickel|Hoffeld|Deuchler|1971|p=1}}

[[File:Limbourg brothers - The Belles Heures of Jean, Duke of Berry - WGA13034.jpg|left|thumb|upright|[[Limbourg brothers]], from the "[[Belles Heures of Jean de France, Duc de Berry|Belles Heures du Duc de Berry]]". French, 1399–1416]]
A coat of arms illustrated on one of the leaves of the "Cloisters Apocalypse" suggests it was commissioned by a member of the de Montigny family of [[Coutances]], [[Normandy]].{{sfn|Nickel|1972|p=64}} Stylistically it resembles other Norman illuminated books, as well as some designs on stained glass, of the period.{{sfn|Deuchler|1971|p=14-15}}  The book was in Switzerland by 1368, possibly at the abbey of [[Zofingen]], in the [[cantons of Switzerland|canton]] of [[Aargau]]. It was acquired by the Met in 1968.{{sfn|Nickel|Hoffeld|Deuchler|1971|p=10}}

{{multiple image
 | align        = right
 | direction    = horizontal
 | header_align = 
 | footer_align = 
 | image1       = Feeding of the Leprous Monk (Lauds) MET.jpg
 | width1       = 100
 | caption1     = ''The Feeding of the Leprous Monk (Lauds)''. Jean Pucelle, "[[Hours of Jeanne d'Evreux]]". French, 1324–28
 | image2       = Psalter of Bonne de Luxembourg.jpg|''The Three Living and the Three Dead'', folio 322r
 | width2       = 127
 | caption2     = ''The Three Living and the Three Dead''. Jean Le Noir. "[[Psalter of Bonne de Luxembourg]]", French, 14th century
}}

The "Hours of Jeanne d'Evreux" is a very small early Gothic book of hours containing 209 folios, of which 25 are full page miniatures. It is lavishly decorated in [[grisaille]] drawings, [[historiated initial]]s and almost 700 [[border image]]s. [[Jeanne d'Évreux]] was the third wife of [[Charles IV of France]], and after their deaths the book went into the possession of Charles' brother, [[Jean, duc de Berry]]. The use of grisaille (shades of gray) drawings allowed the artist to give the figures a highly sculptural form,{{sfn|Barnet| Wu|2005|p=99}} and the miniatures contain structures typical of French [[Gothic architecture]] of the period. The book has been described as "the high point of Parisian court painting", and evidence of "the unprecedentedly refined artistic tastes of the time".{{sfn|Ingo|2014|p=210}}

The "Belles Heures" is widely regarded as one of the finest extant examples of manuscript illumination, and very few books of hours are as richly decorated. It is the only surviving complete book attributed to the Limbourg brothers.{{sfn|Pächt|1950|pp=39–40}} Rockefeller purchased the book from [[Maurice de Rothschild]] in 1954, and donated it to the Metropolitan.{{sfn|Freeman|1956|pp= 93–101}}

The very small "Bonne de Luxembourg" manuscript (each leaf 12.5 × 8.4 × 3.9&nbsp;cm) is attributed to [[Jean Le Noir (illuminator)|Jean le Noir]], and noted for its preoccupation with death. It was commissioned for [[Bonne of Bohemia|Bonne de Luxembourg]], [[Duchess of Normandy]], daughter of [[John the Blind]] and the wife of [[John II of France]], probably at the end of her husband's life, c. 1348–49. It was in a private collection for many years, and thus known only through poor-quality photographic reproductions until acquired by the museum in 1969. Produced in [[tempera]], [[grisaille]], ink and gold leaf on [[vellum]], it had been rarely studied and was until that point misattributed to [[Jean Pucelle]]. Following its acquisition, it was studied by art historians, after which attribution was given to Le Noir.{{sfn|Deuchler|1971|p=267}}

===Tapestries===
[[File:Alexander the Great or Hector of Troy (from the Nine Heroes Tapestries) MET ra47.101.2d.R.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Alexander the Great or Hector of Troy. From the ''Nine Heroes tapestries''. South Netherlandish, c. 1385]]
While examples of textile art are displayed throughout the museum, there are two dedicated rooms given to individual series of [[tapestry|tapestries]], the South Netherlandish  ''Nine Heroes'' (c. 1385){{sfn|Young|1979|p=58}} and [[Flanders|Flemish]]''[[The Hunt of the Unicorn]]'' (c. 1500).{{sfn|Bolton|2018|p= 294}} The Nine Heroes room is entered from the Cuxa cloisters.{{sfn|Young|1979|p=58}} Its 14th-century tapestries are one of the earliest surviving examples of tapestry, and are thought to be the original versions following widely influential and copied designs attributed to Nicolas Bataille.  They were acquired over a period of twenty years, involving the purchase of more than 20 individual fragments which were then sewn together during a long reassembly process. The chivalric figures represent the scriptural and legendary [[Nine Worthies]], who consist of three pagans ([[Hector]], [[Alexander the Great]] and [[Julius Caesar]]), three Jews ([[Joshua]], [[David]] and [[Judas Maccabeus]]) and three Christians ([[King Arthur]], [[Charlemagne]] and [[Godfrey of Bouillon]]). Of these, five figures survive: Hector, Caesar, Joshua, David and Arthur.{{sfn|Stoddard|1972|p= 425}} They have been described as representing "in their variety, the highest level of a rich and powerful social structure of later fourteenth-century France".{{sfn|Young|1979|p=62}}

[[File:The Unicorn is Attacked MET1.jpg|thumb|"The Unicorn is Attacked", from ''[[The Hunt of the Unicorn]]'' tapestries. Brussels or [[Liège]], c.{{nbsp}}1495–1505]]
The ''Hunt of the Unicorn'' room can be entered from the hall containing the ''Nine Heroes'' via an early 16th-century door carved with representations of unicorns.{{sfn|Young|1979|p=65}} The unicorn tapestries consist of a series of large, colourful hangings and fragment textiles{{sfn|Siple|1938|p= 89}} designed in Paris{{sfn|Stoddard|1972|p= 425}} and woven in Brussels or Liège. Noted for their vivid colourization -dominated by blue, yellow-brown, red, and gold hues-and the abundance of a wide variety of flora,{{sfn|Rorimer|1942|p= 13, 18}} they were produced for [[Anne of Brittany]] and completed c. 1495–1505.{{sfn|Rorimer|1942|p= 39}} The tapestries were purchased by Rockefeller in 1922 for about one million dollars, and donated to the museum in 1937.{{sfn|Rorimer|1942|p= 7}} They were cleaned and restored in 1998, and are now hung in a dedicated room on the museum's upper floor.<ref>Preston, Richard. "[http://www.newyorker.com/archive/2005/04/11/050411fa_fact Capturing the Unicorn]". ''[[The New Yorker]]'', April 11, 2005. Retrieved February 26, 2018</ref>

The large "Nativity" panel (also known as "Christ is Born as Man's Redeemer") from c. 1500, South Netherlandish (probably in [[Brussels]]), ''Burgos Tapestry'' was acquired by the museum in 1938. It was originally one of a series of eight tapestries representing the salvation of man,{{sfn|Rorimer|1938|p= 61}} with individual scenes influenced by identifiable panel paintings, including by [[Rogier van der Weyden]].<ref>"[https://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/70007576 Christ Is Born as Man's Redeemer (Episode from the Story of the Redemption of Man)]". Metropolitan Museum of Art. Retrieved August 24, 2018</ref> It was badly damaged in earlier centuries: it had been cut into several irregular pieces and undergone several poor-quality restorations. The panel underwent a long process of restoration from 1971, undertaken by Tina Kane and Alice Blohm of the Metropolitan's Department of Textile Conservation. It is today hung in the Late Gothic hall.<ref>"[https://www.metmuseum.org/metmedia/video/conservation-and-scientific-research/burgos-tapestry-study-in-conservation The Burgos Tapestry: A Study in Conservation]". Metropolitan Museum of Art, June 22, 2011. Retrieved August 24, 2018</ref>

===Stained glass===
[[File:The Virgin Mary and Five Standing Saints above Predella Panels Full.jpg|left|thumb|"The Virgin Mary and Five Standing Saints above Predella Panels", pot-metal and white glass, vitreous paint, silver stain. Rhine Valley, Germany, 1440–46.<ref>"[https://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/473007 The Virgin Mary and Five Standing Saints above Predella Panels]". Metropolitan Museum of Art. Retrieved October 27, 2017</ref>]]
The Cloisters' collection of [[stained glass]] consists of around three hundred panels, generally French and Germanic and mostly from the 13th to early 16th centuries.{{sfn|Husband|2001|p=33}} A number were formed from handmade [[opalescent]] glass. Works in the collection are characterized by vivid colors and often abstract designs and patterns; many have a devotional image as a centerpiece.{{sfn|Hayward|Shepard|Clark|2012|p=36}}  The majority of these works are in the museum's Boppard room, named after the [[Carmelite]] church of Saint Severinus in [[Boppard]], near [[Koblenz]], Germany.{{sfn|Siple|1938|p= 88}} The collection's [[pot-metal]] works (from the High Gothic period) highlight the effects of light,{{sfn|Husband|2013|p=33}} especially the transitions between darkness, shadow and illumination.<ref>Cotter, Holland. "[https://www.nytimes.com/2014/02/28/arts/design/stained-glass-at-the-cloisters.html?_r=0 Luminous Canterbury Pilgrims: Stained Glass at the Cloisters]". ''The New York Times'', February 27, 2014. Retrieved February 26, 2018</ref> The Met's collection grew in the early 20th century when Raymond Picairn made acquisitions at a time when medieval glass was not highly regarded by connoisseurs, and was difficult to extract and transport.{{sfn|Hayward|Shepard|Clark|2012|p=45}}

{{multiple image
 | align        = right
 | direction    = horizontal
 | header_align = 
 | footer_align = 
 | image1       = Roundel with Descent of the Damned.jpg
 | width1       = 146
 | caption1     = "Descent of the Damned", [[roundel]], North Netherlandish, 1500–10
 | image2       = Roundel with the Temptation of Saint Anthony MET.jpg
 | width2       = 140
 | caption2     = "Roundel with the Temptation of Saint Anthony", German, [[Swabia]], 1532
}}

Jane Hayward, a curator at the museum from 1969 who began the museum's second phase of acquisition, describes stained glass as "unquestioningly the preeminent form of Gothic medieval monumental painting".{{sfn|Hayward|Shepard|Clark|2012|p=31}} She bought c.{{nbsp}}1500 [[Heraldry|heraldic]] windows from the [[Rhineland]], now in the Campin room with the ''Mérode Altarpiece''. Hayward's addition in 1980 led to a redesign of the room so that the installed pieces would echo the domestic setting of the altarpiece. She wrote that the Campin room is the only gallery in the Met "where domestic rather than religious art predominates...a conscious effort has been made to create a fifteenth-century domestic interior similar to the one shown in [Campin's] ''Annunciation'' panel."{{sfn|Hayward|Shepard|Clark|2012|p=32}} Other significant acquisitions include late 13th-century [[grisaille]] panels from the Château-de-Bouvreuil in [[Rouen]], glass work from the [[Sées Cathedral|Cathedral of Saint-Gervais-et-Saint-Protais]] at [[Sées]],{{sfn|Hayward|Shepard|Clark|2012|p=32}} and panels from the Acezat collection, now in the Heroes Tapestry Hall.{{sfn|Hayward|Shepard|Clark|2012|p=303}}

==Exterior==
The building is set into a steep hill, and thus the rooms and halls are divided between an upper entrance and a ground-floor level. The enclosing exterior building is mostly modern, and is influenced by and contains elements from the 13th-century church at Saint-Geraud at Monsempron, France, from which the northeast end of the building borrows especially. It was mostly designed by the architect [[Allen & Collens|Charles Collens]], who took influence from works in Barnard's collection. At times to the frustration of the architects and builders, Rockefeller closely managed both the building's design and construction.{{sfn|Husband|2013|p=32}}

[[File:The Cloisters from Garden.jpg|left|thumb|Bonnefont garden and cloisters]]
The building contains architecture elements and settings relocated mostly from four French abbeys, which between 1934 and 1939 were transported, reconstructed and integrated with new buildings in a project overseen by Collins. He told Rockefeller that the new building "should present a well-studied outline done in the very simplest form of stonework growing naturally out of the rocky hill-top. After looking through the books in the Boston Athenaeum&nbsp;...we found a building at Monsempron in Southern France of a type which would lend itself in a very satisfactory manner to such a treatment."{{sfn|Husband|2013|p=32}}

The architects sought to both memorialize the north hill's role in the [[American Revolution]], and provide a sweeping view over the [[Hudson River]]. Construction of the exterior began in 1935. The stonework originates from several European sources, primarily limestone and granite,{{sfn|Husband|2013|p=35}} and includes four Gothic windows from the refectory at [[Sens]], and nine arcades.{{sfn|Husband|2013|p=41}} The dome of the Fuentidueña Chapel was especially difficult to fit into the planned area.{{sfn|Husband|2013|p=38}} The east elevation is mostly formed from limestone and contains nine arcades from the Benedictine priory at [[Froville]], and four [[flamboyant]] French Gothic windows from the Dominican monastery at Sens.{{sfn|Husband|2013|p=41}}

===Cloisters===
====Cuxa====
[[File:Cuxa Cloister MET DP132222.jpg|220px|thumb|The Cuxa Cloister, c. 1130–40]]
Located on the south side of the building's main level, the Cuxa cloisters are the museum's centerpiece both structurally and thematically.{{sfn|Husband|2013|p=33}} They were originally erected at the Benedictine Abbey of [[Abbey of Saint-Michel-de-Cuxa|Sant Miquel de Cuixà]] on [[Canigou|Mount Canigou]], in the northeast French Pyrenees, which was founded in 878.<ref name="met1">"[http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/470314 Cuxa Cloister]". Metropolitan Museum of Art. Retrieved May 15, 2016</ref> The monastery was abandoned in 1791 and fell into disrepair; its roof collapsed in 1835 and its [[bell tower]] fell in 1839.{{sfn|Young|1979|p=47}} About half of its stonework was moved to New York between 1906 and 1907.<ref name="met1" />{{sfn|Dale|2001|p=405}} The installation became one of the first major undertakings by the Metropolitan after it acquired Barnard's collection. After intensive work over the fall and winter of 1925–26, the Cuxa cloisters were opened to the public on April 1, 1926.{{sfn|Husband|2013|p=22}}<ref name="met1926" />

[[File:Cuxa Cloister MET DP132224.jpg|left|thumb|Stone pillars and capitals with [[grotesque]]s]]
The [[Quadrangle (architecture)|quadrangle]]-shaped garden once formed a center around which monks slept in cells. The original garden seemed to have been lined by walkways around [[Arcade (architecture)|adjoining arches]] lined with capitals enclosing the [[Quadrangle (architecture)|garth]]. {{sfn|Bayard|1997|pp= 37–42}} It is impossible now to represent solely medieval species and arrangements; those in the Cuxa garden are approximations by botanists specializing in medieval history.{{sfn|Bayard|1997|pp= 37–42}} The oldest plan of the original building describes [[Lilium|lilies]] and [[rose]]s.{{sfn|Bayard|1997|pp= 37–42}} Although the walls are modern, the capitals and columns are original and cut from pink Languedoc marble from the [[Pyrenees]].{{sfn|Husband|2013|p=22}} The intersection of the two walkways contains an eight-sided fountain.{{sfn|Peck|1996|p=31}}

The capitals were carved at different points in the abbey's history and thus contain a variety of forms and abstract geometric patterns, including scrolling leaves, pine cones, sacred figures such as Christ, the [[Apostle (Christian)|Apostles]], angels, and monstrous creatures including two-headed animals, lions restrained by apes, [[Hybrid beasts in folklore|mythic hybrids]], a mermaid and inhuman mouths consuming human torsos.{{sfn|Dale|2001|p=407}}{{sfn|Horste|1982|p=126}} The motifs are derived from popular fables,<ref name="met1" /> or represent the brute forces of nature or evil,{{sfn|Calkins |2005|=112}} or are based on late 11th- and 12th-century monastic writings, such as those by [[Bernard of Clairvaux]] (1090–1153).{{sfn|Dale|2001|p=402}} The order in which the capitals were originally placed is unknown, making their interpretation especially difficult, although a sequential and continuous narrative was probably not intended.{{sfn|Dale|2001|p=406}} According to art historian Thomas Dale, to the monks, the "human figures, beasts, and monsters" may have represented the "tension between the world and the cloister, the struggle to repress the natural inclinations of the body".{{sfn|Dale|2001|p=410}}

====Saint-Guilhem====
[[File:Cloisters-724.jpg|thumb|Saint-Guilhem Cloisters]]
The Saint-Guilhem cloisters were taken from the site of the [[Benedictine]] monastery of [[Saint-Guilhem-le-Désert]], and date from 804 AD to the 1660s.{{sfn|Barnet| Wu|2005|p= 58}} Their acquisition around 1906 was one of Barnard's early purchases. The transfer to New York involved the movement of around 140 pieces, including capitals, columns and pilasters.{{sfn|Husband|2013|p=8}} The carvings on the marble [[Pier (architecture)|piers]] and column shafts recall Roman sculpture and are coiled by extravagant foliage, including [[vine]]s.{{sfn|
Forsyth|1992|p=10}} The capitals contain [[acanthus (ornament)|acanthus]] leaves and grotesque heads peering out,<ref>Yarrow, Andrew. "[https://www.nytimes.com/1986/06/13/arts/a-date-with-serenity-at-the-cloisters.html?pagewanted=all A Date With Serenity At the Cloisters]". ''The New York Times'', June 13, 1986. Retrieved May 21, 2016</ref> including figures at the [[Presentation at the Temple]], [[Daniel in the Lions' Den]]<ref>"[http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/472181 Saint-Guilhem Cloister]". Metropolitan Museum of Art. Retrieved May 15, 2016</ref> and the [[Hellmouth|Mouth of Hell]],{{sfn|Young|1979|pp=24–25}} and several [[pilaster]]s and columns.{{sfn|Barnet| Wu|2005|p= 58}} The carvings seem preoccupied with the evils of hell. Those beside the mouth of hell contain representations of the devil and tormenting beasts, with, according to Young, "animal-like body parts and cloven hoofs [as they] herd naked sinners in chains to be thrown into an upturned monster's mouth".{{sfn|Young|1979|p=26}}

The Guilhem cloisters are inside the museum's upper level and are much smaller than originally built.{{sfn|Young|1979|p=23}} Its garden contains a central fountain{{sfn|Bayard|1997|p= 81}} and plants potted in ornate containers, including a 15th-century glazed [[earthenware]] vase. The area is covered by a skylight and plate glass panels which conserves heat in the winter months. Rockefeller had initially wanted a high roof and [[clerestory]] windows, but was convinced by [[Joseph Breck (curator)|Joseph Breck]], curator of decorative arts at the Metropolitan, to install a skylight. Breck wrote to Rockefeller that "by substituting a skylight for a solid ceiling...the sculpture is properly illuminated, since the light falls in a natural way; the visitor has the sense of being in the open; and his attention, consequently, is not attracted to the modern superstructure."{{sfn|Husband|2013|p=39}}

====Bonnefont====
[[File:Bonnefont Cloisters.jpg|thumb|View of the Bonnefont cloisters]]
The Bonnefont cloisters were assembled from several French monasteries, but mostly come from a late 12th-century [[Cistercians|Cistercian]] {{ill|Abbaye de Bonnefont|fr}} at Bonnefont-en-Comminges, southwest of [[Toulouse]].{{sfn|Rorimer|Serrell|1972|p=20}} The abbey was intact until at least 1807, and by the 1850s all of its architectural features had been removed from the site, often for decoration of nearby buildings.{{sfn|Young|1979|p=93}} Barnard purchased the stonework in 1937.{{sfn|Young|1979|p=98}} Today the Bonnefont cloisters contain 21 double capitals, and surround a garden that contains many features typical of the medieval period, including a central [[wellhead]], raised flower beds and lined with [[Wattle (construction)|wattle fences]].<ref>McGowan, Sarah. "[https://sourcebooks.fordham.edu/medny/herbgdn1.asp The Bonnefont Cloister Herb Garden]". [[Fordham University]]. Retrieved May 22, 2016</ref> The marbles are highly ornate and decorated, some with [[grotesque]] figures.<ref>"[https://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/474091 Bonnefont Cloister]". Metropolitan Museum of Art. Retrieved May 15, 2016</ref> The inner garden has been set with a [[Mespilus germanica|medlar tree]] of the type found in ''The Hunt of the Unicorn'' tapestries, and is centered around a wellhead placed at Bonnefont-en-Comminges in the 12th century.{{sfn|Young|1979|p=16}} The Bonnefort is on the upper level of the museum and gives a view of the [[Hudson river]] and the cliffs of [[The Palisades (Hudson River)|The Palisades]].{{sfn|Siple|1938|p= 88}}

====Trie====
[[File:The cloisters, trie cloister 02.JPG|thumb|left|Fountain at the Trie cloisters. Eighteen of the original building's eighty-one capitals were moved to New York.{{sfn|Young|1979|p=12}}]]
The Trie cloisters was compiled from two late 15th- to early 16th-century French structures.{{sfn|Rorimer|Serrell|1972|p=22}} Most of its components came from the [[Carmelites|Carmelite]] convent at [[Trie-sur-Baïse]] in south-western France, whose original abbey, except for the church, was destroyed by [[Huguenots]] in 1571.{{sfn|Husband|2013|p=10}} Small narrow [[buttress]]es were added in New York during the 1950s by Breck.{{sfn|Husband|2013|p=38}} The rectangular garden hosts around 80 species of plants and contains a tall limestone cascade fountain at its center.{{sfn|Barnet| Wu|2005|p= 18}} Like those from Saint-Guilhem, the Trie cloisters have been given modern roofing.{{sfn|Husband|2013|p=34}}

The convent at Trie-sur-Baïse featured some 80 white marble capitals{{sfn|Young|1979|p=96}} carved between 1484 and 1490.{{sfn|Rorimer|Serrell|1972|p=22}} Eighteen were moved to New York and contain numerous biblical scenes and incidents form the lives of saints. Several of the carvings are secular, including those of legendary figures such as [[Saint George and the Dragon]],{{sfn|Young|1979|p=96}} the "[[wild man]]" confronting a grotesque monster, and a grotesque head wearing an unusual and fanciful hat.{{sfn|Young|1979|p=96}} The capitals are placed in chronological order, beginning with God in the act of creation at the northwest corner, [[Adam and Eve]] in the west gallery, followed by the [[Binding of Isaac]], and [[Matthew the Apostle|Matthew]] and [[John the Apostle|John]] writing their gospels. Capitals in the south gallery illustrate scenes from the [[Life of Christ in art|life of Christ]].{{sfn|Young|1979|pp=97–9}}

===Gardens===
During periods of political unrest and military invasion, gardens became essential for community survival.{{sfn|Bayard|1997|p=1}} The Cloisters' three gardens, the Judy Black Garden at the Cuxa Cloister on the main level, and the Bonnefont and Trie Cloisters gardens on the lower level,<ref>"[https://www.metmuseum.org/press/general-information/2016/gardens-at-the-met-cloisters Gardens at The Met Cloisters]".  Metropolitan Museum of Art. Retrieved February 26, 2018</ref> were laid out and planted in 1938. They contain a variety of rare medieval species,{{sfn|Bayard|1997|p=vii}} with a total of over 250 genera of plants, flowers, herbs and trees, making it one of the world's most important collections of specialized gardens. The garden's design was overseen by Rorimer during the museum's construction. He was aided by Margaret Freeman, who conducted extensive research into the keeping of plants and their symbolism in the Middle Ages.{{sfn|Bayard|1997|pp= 1–2}} Today the gardens are tended by a staff of [[horticulturalist]]s; the senior members are also historians of 13th- and 14th-century gardening techniques.{{sfn|Bayard|1997|p=2}}

==Interior==
===Gothic chapel===
The Gothic chapel is set on the museum's ground level, and was built to display its stained glass and large sculpture collections. The entrance from the upper level Early Gothic Hall is lit by stained glass double-[[lancet window|lancet]] windows, carved on both sides, and acquired from the church of La Tricherie, France.{{sfn|Husband|2013|p=40}} The ground level is entered through a large door at its east wall. This entrance begins with a pointed Gothic arch leading to high bayed ceilings, ribbed vaults and buttress.{{sfn|Young|1979|p=76}} The three center windows are from the church of [[Bad Sankt Leonhard im Lavanttal|Sankt Leonhard]], in southern Austria, from c. 1340. The glass panels include a depiction of [[Martin of Tours]] as well as complex medallion patterns.{{sfn|Young|1979|p=76}} The glass on the east wall comes from [[Evron Abbey]], Normandy, and dates from around 1325.{{sfn|Young|1979|p=80}} The [[apse]] contains three large sculptures by the main windows; two larger than life-size female saints dating from the 14th century, and a [[Burgundy|Burgundian]] Bishop dating from the 13th.{{sfn|Young|1979|p=89}} The large limestone sculpture of [[Margaret the Virgin|Saint Margaret]] on the wall by the stairs dates to around 1330 and is from the church of {{ill|Santa Maria de Farfanya|ca|Santa Maria de Castelló de Farfanya}} in [[Lleida]], Catalonia.{{sfn|Young|1979|p=76}}

[[File:Cloisters Chapel (3220524245).jpg|thumb|upright|View of the Gothic Chapel, with [[tomb effigy|tomb effigies]] and Gothic stained glass windows]]
Each of the six effigies are supreme examples of [[Funerary art|sepulchral art]].{{sfn|Young|1979|p=82}} Three are from the {{ill|Bellpuig Monastery|ca|Monestir de Santa Maria de Bellpuig de les Avellanes}} in [[Catalonia]].{{sfn|Young|1979|p=82}} The monument directly facing the main windows is the c. 1248–67 sarcophagus of Jean d'Alluye, a [[Knights Templar|knight of the crusades]], who was thought to have returned from the [[Holy Land]] with a relic of the [[True Cross]]. He is shown as a young man, his eyes open, and dressed in [[Mail (armour)|chain armor]], with his [[longsword]] and shield.{{sfn|Young|1979|p=89}} The female effigy of a lady, found in Normandy, dates to the mid 13th century and is perhaps of [[Margaret of Gloucester]].{{sfn|Young|1979|pp=80–84}} Although resting on a modern base,<ref>"[http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/471462 Tomb Effigy of a Lady]". Metropolitan Museum of Art. Retrieved June 5, 2016</ref> she is dressed in high contemporary aristocratic fashion, including a [[Mantle (clothing)|mantle]], [[cotte]], jewel studded belt and an elaborate ring necklace [[brooch]].{{sfn|Reynolds Brown|1992|p=409}}

Four of the effigies were made for the Urgell family, are set into the chapel walls, and are associated with the church of Santa Maria at Castello de Farfanya, redesigned in the Gothic style for [[Ermengol X, Count of Urgell|Ermengol X]] (died c. 1314).{{sfn|Young|1979|p=82}} The elaborate sarcophagus of [[Ermengol VII, Count of Urgell]] (d. 1184) is placed on the left hand wall facing the chapel's south windows. It is supported by three stone lions, and a grouping of mourners carved into the [[Stone slab|slab]], which also shows [[Christ in Majesty]] flanked by the [[Apostles|Twelve Apostles]].{{sfn|Rorimer|Serrell|1972|p=88}} The three other Urgell tombs also date to the mid 13th century, and maybe of [[Álvaro of Urgell|Àlvar of Urgell]] and his second wife, Cecilia of Foix, the parents of Ermengol X, and that of a young boy, possibly [[Ermengol IX, Count of Urgell|Ermengol IX]], the only one of their direct line ancestors known to have died in youth.{{sfn|Young|1979|pp=80–84}} The slabs of the double tomb on the wall opposite Ermengol VII, contain the effigies of his parents, and have been slanted forward to offer a clear view of the stonework. The heads are placed on cushions, which are decorated with arms. The male's feet rest on a dog, while the cushion under the woman's head is held by an angel.{{sfn|Young|1979|p=86}}

===Fuentidueña chapel===
{{Main|The Fuentidueña Apse}}
[[File:The cloisters chapel reconstruction.JPG|thumb|upright|left|[[The Fuentidueña Apse]], Spanish, c. 1175–1200]]
The Fuentidueña chapel is the museum's largest room,{{sfn|Rorimer|1951|p=267}} and is entered through a broad oak door flanked by sculptures which include  leaping animals. Its centerpiece is the [[The Fuentidueña Apse|Fuentidueña Apse]], a semicircular Romanesque recess built between about 1175 to 1200 at the Saint Joan church at [[Fuentidueña]], [[Segovia]].<ref>"[http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/473008 Crucifix]". Metropolitan Museum of Art. Retrieved May 2, 2016</ref> By the 19th century, the church was long abandoned and in disrepair. 

It was acquired by Rockefeller for the Cloisters in 1931, following three decades of complex negotiation and diplomacy between the Spanish church and both countries' art-historical hierarchies and governments. It was eventually exchanged in a deal that involved the transfer of six [[fresco]]es from [[San Baudelio de Berlanga]] to the Prado, on an equally long-term loan.{{sfn|Wixom|1988|p=36}} The structure was disassembled into almost 3,300 mostly sandstone and limestone blocks, each individually cataloged, and shipped to New York in 839 crates.<ref>"Monumental Moving Job". New York: ''Life Magazine'', October 20, 1961</ref> 

It was rebuilt at the Cloisters in the late 1940s{{sfn|Barnet| Wu|2005|p= 36}} It was such a large and complex reconstruction that it required the demolition of the former "Special Exhibition Room". The chapel was opened to the public in 1961, seven years after its installation had begun.{{sfn|Barnet| Wu|2005|p= 38}}

[[File:Crucifix, Spain, ca. 1150-1200; Virgin and Child in Majesty, Master of Pedret Catalunya, ca. 1100 (5459694198).jpg|thumb|upright|''Virgin and Child in Majesty'', Master of Pedret Catalunya, c. 1100]]
The apse consists of a broad arch leading to a [[barrel vault]], and culminates with a half-dome.{{sfn|Young|1979|p=14}}  The capitals at the entrance contain representations of the [[Adoration of the Magi]] and [[Daniel in the lions' den]].{{sfn|Wixom|1988|p=38}} The piers show Martin of Tours on the left and the angel [[Gabriel]] announcing to [[Mary, mother of Jesus|The Virgin]] on the right. The chapel includes other, mostly contemporary, medieval artwork. They include, in the dome, a large fresco dating to between 1130–50, from the Spanish Church of Sant Joan de Tredòs. The fresco's colorization resembles a [[Byzantine]] [[mosaic]] and is dedicated to the ideal of Mary as the mother of God.{{sfn|Young|1979|p=17}} Hanging within the apse is a crucifix made between about 1150 to 1200 for the {{ill|Convent of St. Clara|es|Convento de Santa Clara (Astudillo)}} in [[Astudillo, Palencia|Astudillo]], Spain.{{sfn|Husband|2013|p=42}} Its reverse contains a depiction of the Agnus Dei ([[Lamb of God]]), decorated with red and blue foliage at its frames.{{sfn|Wixom|1988|p=39}} The exterior wall holds three small, narrow and stilted windows,{{sfn|Wixom|1988|p=38}} which are nevertheless designed to let in the maximum amount of light. The windows were originally set within imposing fortress walls; according to the art historian Bonnie Young "these small windows and the massive, fortress-like walls contribute to the feeling of austerity...typical of Romanesque churches."{{sfn|Young|1979|p=14}}

===Langon chapel===
{{Main|Doorway from Moutiers-Saint-Jean}}
[[File:Chapel from Notre-Dame-du-Bourg at Langon MET DP255163.jpg|left|upright|thumb|Langon Chapel, French, 12th century]]
The Langon chapel is on the museum's ground level. Its right wall was built around 1126 for the Romanesque [[Cathédrale Notre-Dame-du-Bourg de Digne]].{{sfn|Young|1979|p=31}} The chapter house consists of a single [[aisle]] [[nave]] and [[transept]]s{{sfn|Barnet| Wu|2005|p= 47}} taken from a small [[Order of Saint Benedict|Benedictine]] parish church built around 1115 at Notre Dame de Pontaut.{{sfn|Young|1979|p=40}} When acquired, it was in disrepair, its upper level in use as a storage place for tobacco. About three-quarters of its original stonework was moved to New York.{{sfn|Barnet| Wu|2005|p= 47}} 

The chapel is entered from the Romanesque hall through [[Doorway from Moutiers-Saint-Jean|a doorway]], a large, elaborate French Gothic stone entrance commissioned by the [[Duke of Burgundy|Burgundian court]]{{sfn|Siple|1938|p=88}} for [[Moutiers-Saint-Jean Abbey]] in [[Burgundy]], France. Moutiers-Saint-Jean was sacked, burned, and rebuilt several times. In 1567, the [[Huguenot]] army removed the heads from the two kings, and in 1797 the abbey was sold as rubble for rebuilding. The site lay in ruin for decades and lost further sculptural elements until Barnard arranged for the entrances' transfer to New York. The doorway had been the main portal of the abbey, and was probably built as the south transept door. 

Carvings on the elaborate white [[Oolite|oolitic]] limestone doorway depict the [[Coronation of the Virgin]] and contains foliated capitals and statuettes on the outer piers; including two kings positioned in the [[embrasure]]s and various kneeling angels. Carvings of angels are placed in the [[archivolt]]s above the kings.{{sfn|Forsyth|1978|pp=33, 38}} The large figurative sculptures on either side of the doorway represent the early [[Franks|Frankish]] kings [[Clovis I]] (d. 511) and his son [[Chlothar I]] (d. 561).<ref>"[http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/470313 Doorway from Moutiers-Saint-Jean]". Metropolitan Museum of Art. Retrieved August 14, 2016</ref>{{sfn|Rorimer|Serrell|1972|p=28}} The [[pier]]s are lined with elaborate and highly detailed rows of statuettes, which are mostly set in [[Niche (architecture)|niche]]s,{{sfn|Forsyth|1978|p=57}} and are badly damaged; most have been decapitated. The heads on the right hand capital were for a time believed to represent [[Henry II of England]].<ref>"[http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/479486 Chapel from Notre-Dame-du-Bourg at Langon] . Metropolitan Museum of Art. Retrieved May 14, 2016</ref> Seven capitals survive from the original church, with carvings of human figures or heads, some of which as have been identified as historical persons, including [[Eleanor of Aquitaine]].{{sfn|Barnet| Wu|2005|p= 47}}

===Romanesque hall===
The Romanesque hall contains three large church doorways, with the main visitor entrance adjoining the Guilhem Cloister. The monumental arched [[Duchy of Burgundy|Burgundian]] doorway is from [[Moutiers-Saint-Jean Abbey|Moutier-Saint-Jean de Réôme]] in France and dates to c. 1150.{{sfn|Siple|1938|p=88}} Two animals are carved into the [[Keystone (architecture)|keystones]]; both rest on their hind legs as if about to attack each other. The capitals are lined with carvings of both real and imagined animals and birds, as well as leaves and other fauna.{{sfn|Young|1979|p=6}} The two earlier doorways are from [[Laféline|Reugny, Allier]], and [[Poitou]] in central France.{{sfn|Landais|1992|p= 43}} The hall contains four large early-13th-century stone sculptures representing the Adoration of the Magi, frescoes of a lion and a [[wyvern]], each from the [[Monastery of San Pedro de Arlanza]] in north central Spain.{{sfn|Siple|1938|p=88}} On the left of the room are portraits of kings and angels, also from the monastery at Moutier-Saint-Jean.{{sfn|Young|1979|p=6}} The hall contains three pairs of columns positioned over an entrance with molded archivolts. They were taken from the Augustinian church at [[Reugny, Indre-et-Loire|Reugny]].{{sfn|Barnet| Wu|2005|p= 78}} The Reugny site was badly damaged during the French Wars of Religion and again during the French Revolution. Most of the structures had been sold to a local man, Piere-Yon Verniere, by 1850, and were acquired by Barnard in 1906.{{sfn|Barnet| Wu|2005|p= 58}}

===Treasury room===
The Treasury room was opened in 1988 to celebrate the museum's 50th anniversary. It largely consists of small luxury objects acquired by the Met after it had built its initial collection, and draws heavily on acquisitions from the collection of Joseph Brummer.<ref>"[https://www.metmuseum.org/press/exhibitions/2006/medieval-treasury-reopens-at-the-cloisters Medieval Treasury Reopens at The Cloisters]". Metropolitan Museum of Art. Retrieved August 19, 2018</ref> The rooms contains the museum's collection of illuminated manuscripts, the French 13th-century arm-shaped silver reliquary,<ref>"[https://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/464334 Arm Reliquary]". Metropolitan Museum of Art. Retrieved August 19, 2018</ref> and a 15th-century deck of [[playing cards]].<ref>"[http://nymag.com/listings/attraction/cloisters/ The Cloisters]". ''[[New York Magazine]]''. Retrieved August 19, 2018</ref>

===Library and archives===
The Cloisters contains one of the Metropolitan's 13 libraries. Focusing on medieval art and architecture, it holds over 15,000 volumes of books and journals, the museum's archive administration papers, curatorial papers, dealer records and the personal papers of Barnard, as well as early glass lantern slides of museum materials, manuscript [[facsimile]]s, scholarly records, maps and recordings of musical performances at the museum.<ref>[http://www.metmuseum.org/research/libraries-and-study-centers/the-cloisters-library-and-archive "The Cloisters Library and Archives"]. Metropolitan Museum of Art. Retrieved May 15, 2016</ref> The library functions primarily as a resource for museum staff, but is available by appointment to researchers,  art dealers, academics and students.{{sfn|Jackson-Beck|1989|p=1}} The archives contain early sketches and [[blueprint]]s made during the early design phase of the museum's construction, as well as historical photographic collections. These include photographs of medieval objects from the collection of [[George Joseph Demotte]], and a series taken during and just after [[World War II]] showing damage sustained to monuments and artifacts, including tomb effigies. They are, according to curator Lauren Jackson-Beck, of "prime importance to the art historian who is concerned with the identification of both the original work and later areas of reconstruction".{{sfn|Jackson-Beck|1989|p=2}} Two important series of prints are kept on [[microfilm]]: the "Index photographique de l'art en France" and the German "[[Marburg Picture Index]]".{{sfn|Jackson-Beck|1989|p=2}}

==Governance==
The Cloisters is governed by the board of the Metropolitan Museum of Art. The Metropolitan's collections are owned by a private corporation of about 950 fellows and benefactors. The board of trustees comprise 41 elected members, several officials of the City of New York, and persons honored as trustees by the museum. The current chairman of the board is the businessman and art collector [[Daniel Brodsky]], who was elected in 2011,<ref>Pogrebin, Robin. "[https://www.nytimes.com/2017/04/02/arts/design/met-museum-campbell-resignation-brodsky-coburn.html A Hushed Departure at the Met Museum Reveals Entrenched Management Culture]". ''The New York Times'', April 02, 2007. Retrieved September 15, 2018</ref> having previously served on its Real Estate Council in 1984 as a trustee of the museum and Vice Chairman of the Buildings Committee.<ref>"[http://www.alumni.nyu.edu/s/1068/alumni/interior.aspx?sid=1068&gid=1&pgid=2630 NYU Alumni: Daniel Brodsky]". [[New York University]]. Retrieved March 30, 2018</ref>

==Acquisition and deaccessioning==
[[File:The Falcon's Bath MET.jpg|thumb|The 15th-century "Falcon's Bath" tapestry was acquired by the museum in 2011]]
The Cloisters regularly acquires new works although as a specialist museum rarely deaccessions.  While the Metropolitan does not publish separate figures for the Cloisters, the entity as a whole spent $39 million on acquisitions for the fiscal year ending in June 2012.<ref>Pogrebin, Robin. "[https://www.nytimes.com/2013/07/23/arts/design/qatar-uses-its-riches-to-buy-art-treasures.html Qatar Uses Its Riches to Buy Art Treasures]". ''[[The New York Times]]'', July 22, 2013. Retrieved May 26, 2018</ref> The Cloisters seeks to balance its collection between religious and secular artifacts and artworks. With secular pieces, it typically favors those that indicate the range of artistic production in the medieval period, and according to art historian Timothy Husband, "reflect the fabric of daily [medieval European] life but also endure as works of art in their own right."{{sfn|Husband|2016|p=25}} In 2011 it purchased the then-recently discovered ''The Falcon's Bath'', a Southern Netherlands [[tapestry]] dated c. 1400–1415. It is of exceptional quality, and one of the best preserved surviving examples of its type.<ref>"[https://www.metmuseum.org/-/media/Files/About%20The%20Met/Annual%20Reports/2010_2011/Director%20and%20President.pdf?la=en Annual Report for the Year 2010–11: Report from the Director and the President]". Metropolitan Museum of Art, November 9, 2011. Retrieved March 30, 2018</ref> Other recent acquisitions of significance include the 2015 purchase of a Book of Hours attributed to [[Simon Bening]].<ref name="SM" />

==Exhibitions, programs and media appearances ==
The museum's architectural settings, atmosphere and acoustics have made it a regular setting both for musical recitals and as a stage for medieval theater. Notable stagings include ''[[Le Miracle de Théophile|The Miracle of Theophilus]]'' in 1942, and John Gassner's adaption of ''[[The Second Shepherds' Play]]'' in 1954.<ref>"[https://www.metmuseum.org/blogs/now-at-the-met/features/2013/medieval-drama Medieval Drama at The Cloisters]". Metropolitan Museum of Art, September 5, 2013. Retrieved February 26, 2018</ref> Recent significant exhibitions include "Small Wonders: Gothic Boxwood Miniatures" which ran in the summer of 2017 in conjunction with the [[Art Gallery of Ontario]] and [[Rijksmuseum]], Amsterdam.<ref>"[https://www.metmuseum.org/about-the-met/policies-and-documents/annual-reports Annual Report for the Year 2016–17 Exhibitions and Installations]". Metropolitan Museum of Art, November 14, 2017. Retrieved March 30, 2018</ref>

The museum is a well-known New York City landmark and has been used as a filming location. In 1948, director [[Maya Deren]] used its ramparts as a backdrop for her experimental film ''Meditation on Violence''.<ref name="metmuseum popcult" /> That year, German director [[William Dieterle]] used the Cloisters as the location for a convent school in his film ''[[Portrait of Jennie]]''. The 1968 film ''[[Coogan's Bluff (film)|Coogan's Bluff]]'' used the site's pathways and lanes for a scenic motorcycle chase.<ref name="metmuseum popcult">"[http://www.metmuseum.org/about-the-museum/now-at-the-met/features/2013/cloisters-in-popular-culture The Cloisters in Popular Culture: 'Time in This Place Does Not Obey an Order']". Metropolitan Museum of Art. Retrieved February 23, 2018</ref>

